obs: In this article there were two light conditions (20% and 50% of total PPDF), however it is not clear if the neighbors were the same for both treatment or if they were independent. Hence, we decided to keep just on treatment, in ths case, 20% of PPDF, that was the most powerful test of interaction. About sampling size, there were 5 replicates, but with 30 seeds in each.
suitable_master_reason: this article uses 2 shrub species as neighbour
differences_within_outcomes: under 20% PPDF

map1: not informed (but see http://www.worldclimate.com/cgi-bin/data.pl?ref=N39E002+2100+08306W / Palma de Mallorca as closest city)
gradient1: coastal shrubland located in fixed dunes
obs: The authors say that, like emergence, differences among microhabitats were larger in the dune than in the olive grove. In the former, the lowest seedling survival occurred in the open (11.1 +/- 4.3%, both years pooled) and there were no differences among the other microhabitats (but see Fig. 2). By contrast, the lowest seedling survival in the olive grove was under Daphne (29.6 +/- 4.6%) whilst the highest was under Olea 46.2 +/- 5.8%), but see Fig. 2. I have to transform the proportion in absolute number using total n = number of emerged seedlings (but I only have mean).
suitable_meta_reason: data about survival might be dependant on emergence
differences_within_outcomes: pair-wise combination

obs: The authors say that, like emergence, differences among microhabitats were larger in the dune than in the olive grove. In the former, the lowest seedling survival occurred in the open (11.1 +/- 4.3%, both years pooled) and there were no differences among the other microhabitats (but see Fig. 2). By contrast, the lowest seedling survival in the olive grove was under Daphne (29.6 +/- 4.6%) whilst the highest was under Olea 46.2 +/- 5.8%), but see Fig. 2. I have to transform the proportion in absolute number using total n = number of emerged seedlings (but I only have mean).
differences_within_outcomes: pair-wise combination, performance estimator is growth_size and different experiment conducted on another year

obs: Obs1: The sampling design is nested and authors present marginal means. I do not know which sample size should be used. In table 3 authors inform degrees of freedom and that could help us determine sample size. Still, I (Camila) find really hard to do so because the residual error of random factor is missing. It would take a lot of study for us to understand this. For now, let's use sample size as the number of frames in the 3 transects per succesional stage (considering the proportion of frames with and without Empetrum described in the beginning of results section). Obs2: Density of neighbor plants in each plot is not informed.
differences_within_outcomes: different part of dune

map1: from 1400 to 2380 mm (see mean based on these values)
obs: Obs1: this study compares occurrence of target life-forms with and without adult neighbors along distinct distances from the seashore. Since I'm not interested in the stress influence and also in order to avoid replication of similar data, I took together the data from all distances (Figure 2). Obs2: A neighbour could have many plants under this canopy. Although it is the only adult tree individual, those other plants could represent a patch. Hence, we stated "isolated_obs" as the "neighbor_type".
differences_within_outcomes: diferent life-forms, tree

gradient1: not informed (the author say "El Rompido Spit presents diverse geomorphologic formations, ranging from high beach and active dune communities to interior semi-stabilized and stabilized dunes, interdune wet depressions, salt marshes and brackish depressions (Gallego Fernández et al. 2006). The semistabilized and stabilized interior dunes represent the main habitat on the spit surface (57 %), and here the vegetation is dominated by R. monosperma, T. carnosus, Helichrysum italicum or Artemisia campestris subsp. maritima, spring annuals, and perennial herbaceous species", but don't inform in which kind of dune they conducted the study)
obs: The authors also measured chlorophyll a fluorescence, photoinibition, gas exchange, leaf mass area, leaf chlorophyll a and b and carotenoids contents, leaf C and N contents and stem water potential in four seasons during 2006/2007.
suitable_meta_reason: there is other outcome with data collected after 5 years, which is preferable
differences_within_outcomes: different period with 5 years of gap between them

gradient1: not informed (the author say "El Rompido Spit presents diverse geomorphologic formations, ranging from high beach and active dune communities to interior semi-stabilized and stabilized dunes, interdune wet depressions, salt marshes and brackish depressions (Gallego Fernández et al. 2006). The semistabilized and stabilized interior dunes represent the main habitat on the spit surface (57 %), and here the vegetation is dominated by R. monosperma, T. carnosus, Helichrysum italicum or Artemisia campestris subsp. maritima, spring annuals, and perennial herbaceous species", but don't inform in which kind of dune they conducted the study)
obs: The authors repeated the measures 5 years later. N is inferred from survival (outcome 347_5). Although authors presented size data, we considered valid to assume this value as a growth measure because five years before they selected plants with sililar sizes.

This community consists of a diverse mosaic of moss and lichen species carpeting the soil surface. Common species belong to the genera Cladonia, Racomitrium and Hypnum. Vascular plants grow within this moss and lichen crust and include a high diversity of winter annuals (20–40% of the flora in UK dunes) and perennial herbs and grasses (Watkinson & Davy 1985). The species included were: Arenaria serpyllifolia (L.), Asterolinum stellatum (L.), Cerastium diffusum (L.), Cerastium semidecandrum (L.), Erodium cicutarium (L.), Geranium molle (L.), Myosotis ramosissima (Rochel), Phleum arenarium (L.), Polycarpon tetraphyllum (L.), Saxifraga tridactylites (L.), Senecio vulgaris (L.), Veronica arvensis (L.), Viola tricolor (L.), Viola kitaibeliana (Schultes) and Vulpia fasciculata (Forskal). The species included were: Arenaria serpyllifolia (L.), Asterolinum stellatum (L.), Cerastium diffusum (L.), Cerastium semidecandrum (L.), Erodium cicutarium (L.), Geranium molle (L.), Myosotis ramosissima (Rochel), Phleum arenarium (L.), Polycarpon tetraphyllum (L.), Saxifraga tridactylites (L.), Senecio vulgaris (L.), Veronica arvensis (L.), Viola tricolor (L.), Viola kitaibeliana (Schultes) and Vulpia fasciculata (Forskal). obs: The authors did an experiment with seeds under Allagoptera clumps and in open areas. They used different seeds and different conditions. We considered the most manipulated condition (seed buried 5 cm under the soil surface and without mesocarp) because these conditions simulate dispersion by Ateuchus aqualidus bug. There were 8 replications per treatment combination with 25 seed in each one. I used proportion of emerged seeds in each sampling unit as response variable (this way pseudoreplications were incorporated to response).
data_location: data provided by authors and figure 1
differences_within_outcomes: seed condition (soil surface with mesocarp)
ask_data: yes, data form figure 2 and life stage
answer_obs: authors sent data in 2019 to Camila and answered life stage
